		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=42828&amp;sid=d51e2fc3dc63f63e37b9c13db2769690#42828"><img src="templates/SpacePilot3K/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Sat Jan 07, 2006 6:29 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Fleet Commanding</span></td>
				<td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=42828&amp;sid=d51e2fc3dc63f63e37b9c13db2769690"><img src="templates/SpacePilot3K/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Based on what I've seen and heard about suggestions for this game, I know this won't go anywhere. It might've even been mentioned in the past but I don't have time to read hundreds of suggestions from the past. But here it is anyway. 
<br />

<br />
I realize this would be a pretty big change, but what would happen if Commander Jim were able to weild 20 Doomstars, 30 Mobile Fortresses, etc etc, OR 2,000 Gunboats? That's right, the number of ships you can command depends on their class. All of a sudden, things get a lot more... not complicated, but new oppertunities arise. Before, you wouldn't think of sending out fleets of Gunboats against much larger targets (except in the special circumstances of fleet fodder, cloaking or advanced tactics). But if you're able to match, not 20, but 5,000 gunboats against those 20 Doomstars, then things get a little more interesting. All sorts of new tactics might evolve if you didn't have to worry about sending out the most high-powered ships available. You could potentially use all the ships across the Gunboat-to-Doomstar spectrum in a battle, with special roles for each. Why? You're not afraid that your fleet of small ships will die against a fleet of larger ships. You've got them outnumbered, even if your troops are smaller.
<br />

<br />
Consider a natural analogy. You, a person, attack a beehive. Stupid thing to do, right? Although the bees are much smaller and one-on-one you can take them out with a well-placed flyswatter, as you add more your odds start to get a little less comfortable. Maybe you DO manage to kill all the bees somehow, but by sheer numbers they inflict damage regardless. 20 people going after 20 bees? No brainer. 20 People going after 2000 bees? Ouch.
<br />

<br />
But let's take it back to Archspace for a moment. Now obviously, you can't have one person commanding 20 ships by himself when they're Doomstar sized. There's a command structure in place. The fleet commander tells the ships where to go and what to shoot at, the captains of the ships tell their officers to tell their gunners and engine crew and targeting teams etc etc what to do. There's a whole command structure in place when you're dealing with something as large as a Doomstar, and that command structure is basically ignored in Archspace. You build a Doomstar, it comes with the crew all ready to go. Likewise, when you build thousands of tiny ships, you should assume that they're already divided up and organized intelligently. For every 10 gunboats, you've got a localized commander who tells them in particular what to attack and defend. For every 10 of those groups, you've got someone else coordinating what the commanders should be trying to accomplish. And for every 20 of those people, you have a single Fleet Commander who organizes the efforts of the entire group of 2000 gunboats. And all of a sudden it's 1 person telling 20 what to do, just like with the Doomstar fleet.
<br />

<br />
Of course, these numbers are all off the top of my head, they might be much too low or high for balancing issues, so don't quote me on the exact figures. But it still seems, if only for the sake of making battle richer in variety, that small ships should be more numerous.
<br />

<br />
Instead of "Fleet Commanding" you switch the name to "Command Points" or something like that. Then give different ship classes a "Command Value." Then when you go to put ships in a fleet, it's a straightforward calculation of (Command Points / Command Value) for the player or AS to figure out how many ships you get.
<br />

<br />
A technically simple change that adds a whole bunch of tactical potential to fleet battles...</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
