			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Alright, you two brought up some good points, so I'll try to clear them up now.
<br />

<br />
I said the numbers were tentative. Apparently it didn't sink in fully. It's all in the numbers, you see. If the system were polished to perfection, it would work like this: Regardless of what class of ship you make, if you make a fleet full of them, the firepowers should be approximately equal between the two fleets. They should also take approximately the same amount of resources to make. This eliminates the problem you pointed out--you can't just mass thousands of tiny ships and pick apart much more valuable doomstars. If you want to make that fleet of ships that's closer in strength to a doomstar, it's gotta cost about the same as well. And here I do acknowledge an issue that I didn't see before, and would require addressing. The building prices of the ships might not stay the same. Then again, building looots of little ships in less time and with less resources than a Doomstar which somehow have much more power... that's never felt right to me either. Of course, adjusting the prices of ships to reflect what they were actually capable of doing would sorta reduce the effects of fluffing (which is two birds with one stone in my book).
<br />

<br />
I don't think it would "absolutely ruin the game" if it were implemented correctly. If ship prices reflected ship power, which they should in my humble opinion, you could crank out thousands of small things or several big things and it wouldn't make a huge difference. Big players can still produce more "firepower" per turn than small ones, so it's not like some new player with thousands of gunboats would be at an advantage over a very high level player with Doomstars.
<br />

<br />
One thing that just occured to me is this: If you have a single Doomstar, that thing has all its weapons online and firing until it blows up with the reasonably simple combat system in place now. With a fleet of lots of little ships, their attack power is slowly whittled away to nothing as it dies. So you see, even if the power WAS balanced with price and fleet size, larger ships would still have that advantage. Then again, smaller ships would be more maneuverable and faster. I don't see tihs as a problem, though, it just makes it a more tactic oriented game than "Lots of Doomies. Then add some fodder." which is probably what a lot of low to mid-level players do.
<br />

<br />
Star Wars example time! If the Empire has a Deathstar and Star Destroyers, why does it insist in making lots of Tie Fighters which go down with one well-placed shot? Because there's more to battle strategy than "Make them very big and powerful."
<br />

<br />
Anybody who's ever played Homeworld Cataclysm might know what I mean. You take out the final enemy in the game, in a MASSIVE star ship by, of all things, stunning it with fleets of fighters, and pecking it to death with the overwhelming number of smaller ships.
<br />

<br />
Also, consider how advanced these civilizations are <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" border="0" /> We humans tend to think that the bigger weapon is always the better choice, or the more powerful weapon is the better choice... many people think of things in simple terms like that. Did it ever occur to anyone that an advanced alien civilization might prove to be FAR more effective with swarms of small ships who are simply too fast to be shot than a single ship? Back to the Homeworld series, anyone who's played the original game might remember an alien race that lives in a nebula. They prove very hard to fight because they have clouds of "Swarmers," these tiny, weak ships. They're hard to fight because they're fast and numerous. Now, this isn't all to say that for some in-game races (back to AS!) small ships should be disproportionally powerful. It's merely to suggest that building the biggest ship might not be the smartest move.
<br />

<br />
One advantage this DOES lend to developing players, however, is the ability to fight back against larger ones. Assume that at your current point in the game, you only have 15 commanders, and 10 of them are absolute garbage for defense and other important attributes. You can consolidate your fleets into few but large groups of ships, instead of sending half of them out with idiots at the helm. Or if you've got 20 defense fleets of crappy ships and simply can't put any more out, it allows you more of a fair fight against someone larger who decides to attack you...</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
